Post_ID: 2767863214936816650	|Post_Code: CZpbO3hLfwK	|Owner_ID: 22580829951	|Likes: 6	|Time_Stamp: 1644175029	|Tags: ['#Mournes', '#Mournes', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#mountains', '#outdoors', '#walking', '#hiking', '#leavenotrace']	|Caption: Graffiti in the #Mournes <br>This picture is of a handrail we replaced last year at a gateway to the Trassey valley. As well as having rotted away, the previous support was covered in graffiti, apparently documenting dates a particular couple visited. The same has occurred on the new rail despite previous etchings having been sanded off. The occurrence is not isolated to this location and the same initials (and occasionally the apparently corresponding names, Glen and Elaine) have appeared on stiles, way markers and other surfaces throughout the #Mournes. We are pleased to note that graffiti is not a particular issue in the area, but it would be sad if it became the case. As well as creating work for our small team who maintain the visitor infrastructure, feedback from other visitors is overwhelmingly clear that this - and other memorials/ markings â€“ intrude significantly on the experience of enjoying an unspoiled landscape. We appreciate that the practice is motivated for this couple by a love of the Mournes as well as each other but would suggest that appreciation of the place is best observed by a #LeaveNoTrace approach. Perhaps photographs and a diary for recording the other love? If you happen to see this Elaine and Glen, we wish you every happiness and ask that you enjoy future visits to the Mournes without visibly marking them. #mountains #outdoors #walking #hiking #leavenotrace

In areas that experience high levels of visitation, such as the campground or the Bear Gulch Reservoir, ground squirrels have become habituated to seek food from humans.<br><br>Never feed squirrels or any wildlife you find in Pinnacles, and maintain a respectful distance from them when possible.<br><br>Remember to always pack out what you pack in, and use our wildlife-proof garbage and recycling containers to dispose of waste, ensuring the lid is latched afterwards.<br><br>Do you have a Pinnacles haiku to help your fellow visitors plan for our learn about the park? These boulders are physically detached from one another, separated sometimes by centimeters-wide crevasses, sometimes by a couple meters that almost dare you to jump, sometimes by tens of meters, all overlooking the boulder-strewn chasms dug out by the Green or Colorado, unseen in the distance.<br><br>Only three days and two nights, but this little excursion is going to stay with me for many years to come. <br><br>#bikepacking #bikepackingbags,  #ursusbikepacks, #faitenfrance, #artisansducycle, #konaexplosif, #Kona, #whiterimtrail, #canyonlands, #canyonlandsnationalpark, #canyonlandsnps, #leavenotrace, #utah, #moab

Post_ID: 2767125029629049190	|Post_Code: CZmzY24Iblm	|Owner_ID: 45464644251	|Likes: 29	|Time_Stamp: 1644087030	|Tags: ['#bikepacking', '#bikepackingbags', '#ursusbikepacks', '#faitenfrance', '#artisansducycle', '#konaexplosif', '#Kona', '#whiterimtrail', '#canyonlands', '#canyonlandsnationalpark', '#canyonlandsnps', '#leavenotrace', '#utah', '#moab']	|Caption: (continued from previous post....)<br><br>Lack of water is the main challenge to deal with for a self-supported trip. A common strategy is to hike down from the plateau and cache water at designated camps before cycling. I did this for two campsites (two separate round trip hikes for each campsite) which gives an awesome perspective of the riding to come. Short, chilly days and long cold nights are another challenge to contend with in the winter, but the total absence of crowds is the reward for braving the low temps, I had the entire place to myself to freeze my ass off alone for three days. <br><br>Regardless of the direction chosen, the loop starts by dropping â€œintoâ€ the rim zone and finishes with a climb back â€œoutâ€, and one really does have the impression of entering into another realm, separated from the world above.  But the trip is more than the sum of it's distances and elevation change. Anyone who's read Calvin and Hobbes might remember Calvin's intrepid alter-ego, Spaceman Spiff, ever crash-landing on barren, alien worlds of cliffs, buttes, improbable rock spires, and monsters! Alas, no monsters to be had (only huge ravens a few Bighorn Sheep), but one does get a sense of exploring an planet in it's primal, formative state. You become (or should become) very aware of your gear, essentially your life-support, your water supply, your level of energy or fatigue, the distances separating you from camp, from water, from warmth, from safety. It is one of those all-to-rare places where you really feel like you are on a dynamic and indifferent planet, our own, not a sanitized, secured terrarium for Homo Sapiens. <br>(continued on next post...)<br>#bikepacking #bikepackingbags,  #ursusbikepacks, #faitenfrance, #artisansducycle, #konaexplosif, #Kona, #whiterimtrail, #canyonlands, #canyonlandsnationalpark, #canyonlandsnps, #leavenotrace, #utah, #moab

Post_ID: 2767121571819685661	|Post_Code: CZmymiiogcd	|Owner_ID: 45464644251	|Likes: 31	|Time_Stamp: 1644086618	|Tags: ['#bikepacking', '#bikepackingbags', '#ursusbikepacks', '#faitenfrance', '#artisansducycle', '#konaexplosif', '#Kona', '#whiterimtrail', '#canyonlands', '#canyonlandsnationalpark', '#canyonlandsnps', '#leavenotrace', '#utah', '#moab']	|Caption: Any cycling trip can elevate even a relatively mundane or familiar area to the realm of adventure, awakening or reawakening a deeper connection to, relationship with and appreciation for that land.  Bikepacking through one of the most spectacular landscapes imaginable, and those days in the saddle and nights in the tent can quickly become some of the most transcendent experiences one can have, a voyage that simply cannot be reduced to the metrics of maps and distances, one that takes place in you soul. <br><br>The â€œWhite Rimâ€ (Canyonlands National Park, Utah) had been on my radar for a few years, as something I could do during one of my trips back to the US, usually in the winter to avoid the Las Vegas heat.  No wide angle lenses, HD screen, no poetry or prose can ever really capture what being immersed in such an environment is like. Nevertheless, I humbly offer my trip report and a few photos. <br><br>The route is only about 160km long, the riding is never very technical, and it is often ridden in a day by people much fitter or hurried than myself. I opted for two nights under that black sidereal canopy, a more leisurely pace leaving time for wandering, wonder, and contemplation.<br> <br>Vehicle access is via a vast plateau forming a kind of elevated peninsula stretching southward into the triangular confluence of the Green and Colorado rivers. This plateau is delimited by sheer bluffs with only a handful of roads and trails descending 400m down to the White Rim. From there, the route follows the characteristically whiteish, crumbling rim of even deeper chasms eroded away by the Green and the Colorado, which are only rarely visible along the route, mostly hidden by their own incisions that they've dug into the older, deeper layers of rock. <br><br>(continued on next post...)<br>#bikepacking #bikepackingbags,  #ursusbikepacks, #faitenfrance, #artisansducycle, #konaexplosif, #Kona, #whiterimtrail, #canyonlands, #canyonlandsnationalpark, #canyonlandsnps, #leavenotrace, #utah, #moab

Post_ID: 2767053924818275523	|Post_Code: CZmjOJXJMzD	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 495	|Time_Stamp: 1644078554	|Tags: ['#rockart', '#petroglyphs', '#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#oldspanishtrail', '#NewMexicoTrue', '#nmoutside', '#nmnomad', '#instagramersnm', '#TravelNM', '#beautiful', '#nmco', '#nmoutdoors', '#onlyinnewmexico', '#newmexicomagazine']	|Caption: GC Petroglyphs 1, NM. This part of New Mexico may be the most historically and culturally diverse region in all of the United States in regards to the rock art that can be found here. The Old Spanish Trail ran through this land, bringing trade from New Mexico to California, which means lots of horses and pack mules, and lots of people traveling through these canyons. The recorded route began in the late 1700â€™s with explorers, Spanish military, and religious missionaries. Eventually trade became the primary reason people used the trail, often transporting regional merchandise, contraband, and slaves, and bringing back horses from California. Even before all this, indigenous peoples inhabited these canyons and thrived in this desert region, trading with the interlopers who passed through. This maze of arroyos and canyons is my favorite area to explore, and a vast mix of rock art can be found within the recesses of this topographic maze. Inscriptions from early travelers and wranglers, Navajo pictographs and petroglyphs, and Ancestral Puebloan glyphs all share the same sandstone canvases, often presenting a stunning visual timeline of the people who passed this way. And LOTS of horse inscriptions!<br><br>Slide 1- Antler Man has me stumped.<br><br>Slide 2- notice the horse and stag superimposed over each other.<br><br>Slide 5- Ancestral Puebloan polydactyl footprint<br><br>Slide 6- â€œNO 1000 HORSE OR MULE PACKâ€.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #oldspanishtrail #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine

Post_ID: 2766578192146568051	|Post_Code: CZk3DUyPRNz	|Owner_ID: 5636844661	|Likes: 1353	|Time_Stamp: 1644021842	|Tags: ['#AAGFilmFridays', '#TheAnselAdamsGallery', '#HorsetailFall', '#GalenRowell', '#AnselAdams', '#Yosemite', '#YosemiteNationalPark', '#LeaveNoTrace']	|Caption: It's about that time of year again...<br><br>Horsetail Fall season is just around the corner... Conditions permitting that is.  What is Horsetail Fall you may ask?  HF is a seasonal waterfall towards the east end of El  Capitan. Occasionally during mid- to late February, it can glow orange when it's backlit by sunset. This unique lighting effect happens only on evenings with a clear sky when the waterfall is flowing. Even slight haze or cloudiness can greatly diminish or eliminate the effect.<br><br>With how sunny it's been lately and the lack of recent precipitation, only time will tell if the phenomenon occurs.  If you are planning to visit the park during Horsetail Fall, expect very busy crowds.  With that being said, please practice Leave No Trace principles.<br><br>Leave No Trace - <br>1. Plan ahead and prepare<br>2. Travel and camp on durable surfaces (camping is not allowed at the Horsetail Fall viewing areas).<br>3. Dispose of waste properly<br>4. Leave what you find<br>5. Minimize campfire impacts (campfires are not allowed at the Horsetail Fall viewing areas).<br>6. Respect Wildlife<br>7. Be considerate of others<br><br>"With Yosemite, we have one of the most extraordinary places on Earth, but Yosemite possesses a "fatal beauty" which invites self-destruction unless we make a strenuous effort to control visitation and use." - Ansel Adams<br><br>Last Light on Horsetail Fall by Galen Rowell <br>https://www.anseladams.com/horsetail-fall-by-galen-rowell/<br><br>For information on Horsetail fall this year, please visit the site below. <br>https://www.nps.gov/yose/planyourvisit/horsetailfall.htm<br><br>#AAGFilmFridays #TheAnselAdamsGallery #HorsetailFall #GalenRowell #AnselAdams #Yosemite #YosemiteNationalPark #LeaveNoTrace

Post_ID: 2766478950356451418	|Post_Code: CZkgfKql4Ba	|Owner_ID: 253109645	|Likes: 41	|Time_Stamp: 1644010109	|Tags: ['#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea', '#ArabiaMountain', '#PanolaMountain', '#NationalHeritageArea', '#NationalPark', '#NationalHistoricSite', '#StatePark', '#GAStateParks', '#GeorgiaStatePark', '#Parks', '#Hiking', '#HikeLife', '#WanderNorthGA', '#AtlantaTrails', '#RespectThePark', '#LeaveNoTrace', '#OptOutside', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#LNT']	|Caption: Take a virtual, time-lapse hike through second-growth forest in the Arabia Mountain National Heritage Area.<br>.<br>What is second-growth forest? Most of the forests that stood when white settlers first arrived in Georgia were what's called "old growth," meaning stands of large, very mature trees without major clearing or logging. While the Muscogee did clear land and use timber prior to white settlement, of course, it was not at the same, massive agricultural scale. As the Georgia Piedmont was cleared for farmland - including by enslaved laborers, such as those at Flat Rock (@flatrockarchives) - many of these old growth trees disappeared. As farmland began to wane in the mid-1900's, some places have seen trees regrow. This is called "second-growth forest," or the forest the returns to a landscape following removal. <br>.<br>Not all second-growth forests come about because of human activity. In places that experience a severe wildfire or flood, second-growth forest arises once the disturbance has passed. In time, second-growth forest can become old growth forest again. As you walk through the woods in Davidson-Arabia Mountain Nature Preserve (@arabiaranger) and Panola Mountain State Park (@panolamountainstatepark), look at the trees around you. How young or old is this forest? Looking at the trees can tell you about the history of the land.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#ArabiaMountainNationalHeritageArea #ArabiaMountain #PanolaMountain #NationalHeritageArea#NationalPark #NationalHistoricSite #StatePark #GAStateParks #GeorgiaStatePark #Parks #Hiking #HikeLife #WanderNorthGA #AtlantaTrails #RespectThePark #LeaveNoTrace #OptOutside #RecreateResponsibly #LNT

Located near the village of Abergwyngregyn between Conwy and Bangor on the A55, walkers can start on the trail from one of two car parks on the outskirts of the village. As the trail nears the cliffside, the roar of the water cascading from 120 feet above fills the air. You probably already have a bunch of great options! â <br>.â <br>.â <br>But I often get asked about reusable alternatives to common things like ziploc bags or packaged tea or take-out containers.  And there are SO MANY reusable alternatives to our disposable lifestyle. â <br>.â <br>.â <br>Cloth snack bag or jar or beeswax wrap instead of ziploc bags; loose tea and tea strainers instead of packaged tea; pyrex or stainless steel containers that you take to the restaurant instead of disposable take out containers.  And so forth ğŸ˜Š.â <br>.â <br>.â <br>We have to be willing to let go of some convenience  and see the cost of convenience.  Maybe you have to do more dishes instead of throwing things out.  Or you have to (*gasp*) open your produce bag to see what's inside instead of having a plastic see-through bag.  In my view, it's worth the extra time and effort if it means preserving our planet and oceans and mitigating the impacts of climate change and plastic pollution.â <br>.â <br>.â <br>Click the link in my bio if you'd like to add a few wax wraps to your stash of plastic fighting super heroes ğŸ˜‰. â <br>.â <br>.â <br>#stopplasticpollution #climatechangeisreal #notraceshop #switchtoreusables #conveniencekills #reducereusereycle #leavenotrace #compostable #compostathome #ditchdisposables #beeswaxwraps #veganwaxwraps #goingzerowaste #lowwaste #lowimpact #zerowaste #circulareconomy #zerowastebusiness #zerowastehomeâ

We put together a short list of some our of favorite LNT ethics to keep in mind when hiking to popular locations:<br><br>ğŸ•STAY ON THE TRAIL â€“ Although many people go their own way and cut switchbacks on popular&nbsp;trails, please stay on the official route and don't contribute to the formation of social trails which cause both erosion and drainage issues, and contribute to a loss of vegetation. Hiking in single file â€“ even when with a large group â€“ also helps prevent the trail from widening.<br><br>ğŸ•PARK RESPONSIBLY â€“ Many popular hikes still only have small parking lots that fill up quickly during peak seasons. Do not park on grass, dirt, or other vegetation, and never block other hikers in. The unfortunate&nbsp;truth is sometimes hikers will have to turn around and come back to hike the trail later when the lot is full&nbsp;â€“ in which case it really does pay to arrive early.<br><br>ğŸ•DON'T BLOCK THE VIEW â€“ Imagine hiking multiple miles one way up a grueling mountain only to see that a fellow hiker set their hammock up right in front of the view point... don't be that guy. However, what is unusual is the increasing frequency of ultra long dry spells since 2010. Today marks 30 days since it last rained greater than 0.08 inches in San Francisco city.  Prior to 2010 (encompassing 60 years of records) there were only four years where the mid winter dry spell exceeded 30 days, but since 2010 there are now five! Whatâ€™s more, there is very high confidence it will stay dry for at least the next 10 days and likely longer. A 40+ day dry spell only occurred once prior to 2010 but if the forecasts verify this will be the third instance since 2010.  Itâ€™s very difficult to get an average season of precipitation when the winter dry spells are so long, and very difficult to escape multi-year droughts when these ultra long dry spells are occurring so frequently. In the past decade the core of wet season has effectively collapsed in the majority of years. #climatechange #californiaweather #cawx #keepitwild #californiawild #ventanawilderness #leavenotrace #recreateresponsibly #aridification

Post_ID: 2765655680381011666	|Post_Code: CZhlTAwJsbS	|Owner_ID: 50216942696	|Likes: 13	|Time_Stamp: 1643911870	|Tags: []	|Caption: Rampart Range Road<br>â €<br>Distance:  35.4km point to point<br>Difficulty:  easy<br>Starting Point:  Garden of the Gods<br>Ending Point:  Near Woodland Park<br>â €<br>This is an easy dirt road drive with views overlooking the Colorado Springs area and, on a clear day, views of Pikes Peak.  4wd is not necessary, but note that much of road is washboard so it makes for a bumpy ride.  You can choose either point to start your drive.  There are a lot of camping spots along this drive which can make for a decent amount of traffic, especially on weekends.  Just make sure to be cautious of other vehicles and atvs.  Even though this is considered an "easy" drive, never drive any faster than you are comfortable going.  Instead of being pressured to drive faster by others simply slow down and pull over enough to let those vehicles pass.

Very odd panel I found that I canâ€™t really categorize. The rock itâ€™s pecked into isnâ€™t very patinated, so itâ€™s hard to estimate age, but the glyphs look dark enough to be at least a couple hundred years old, and the application technique looks legit. This is one of those panels that looks like a complete piece, like all the details are part of a singular composition. I sometimes get caught up trying to figure out what culture a panel belongs to, but I need to remember that all this rock art was created by individuals, so trying to find common visual characteristics to help identify origin doesnâ€™t always work. Sometimes people donâ€™t fit into any category, and the same goes for rock art. Everyone has their place in the timeline, but some might not have fit the general cultural mold of that era. <br><br>Speaking of the panel itself, I canâ€™t help but see a sunrise/sunset at the bottom. There are two zoomorphs, a snake and perhaps a sheep (you can see faint horns, but those may have been added later). The 15 crescent shapes are what really have me wondering. This one is just such an odd panel that doesnâ€™t match up stylistically with any of the other panels that can be found in the area.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #navajo #dinetah #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

There's no better place to do this than Aber Falls; a spectacular waterfall nestled away on the edge of the majestic Carneddau Mountain Range. <br><br>The Aber Falls trail is a gentle, 3 mile family-friendly walking route. Located near the village of Abergwyngregyn between Conwy and Bangor on the A55, walkers can start on the trail from one of two car parks on the outskirts of the village. From here a gravel pathway meanders alongside the Afon Rhaeadr Mawr, through whimisical woodland and lush meadows from which walkers can catch the occasional glimpse of the falls ahead. As the trail nears the cliffside, the roar of the water cascading from 120 feet above fills the air. Post_ID: 2765464095402867652	|Post_Code: CZg5vFVlbvE	|Owner_ID: 32004548302	|Likes: 18	|Time_Stamp: 1643889031	|Tags: ['#pickupafteryourdog', '#reducepollution']	|Caption: Do you scoop other dogsâ€™ poop? ğŸ’©<br>I do! ğŸ™‹ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸<br><br>Not gonna lie. Itâ€™s one of my least favorite things to do. But if I see poop nearby when my dogs are doing their business on a walk, I will bag it along with my dogâ€™s waste. <br><br>Why? Because leaving dog poop on the ground wreaks havoc on our environment! <br><br>Some people think dog waste is a natural fertilizer - but itâ€™s not! Dogs eat a high protein diet so their waste is highly acidic and can actually burn your lawn.<br><br>And dog waste left on the ground will eventually find its way into our local waterways through stormwater drains.  According to the EPA, dog waste contains two main types of pollutants that harm local waterways - nutrients and pathogens. Excess nutrients can cause algae blooms while pathogens can make local waters unswimmable and cause illness to humans who come in contact with them. <br><br>So letâ€™s all pitch in and pick up after our pooches. <br>#pickupafteryourdog #reducepollution

Post_ID: 2765090011169598995	|Post_Code: CZfkrcPvq4T	|Owner_ID: 4010258026	|Likes: 17	|Time_Stamp: 1643844437	|Tags: ['#ecofriendly', '#savetheplanet', '#leavenotrace', '#ecofamily', '#motherearth', '#slowlife', '#naturelover']	|Caption: My family does not practice Leave No Trace or discuss it with my kids. Why?&nbsp;<br>.<br>Apart from the role it currently plays in gate keeping the outdoors from marginalized communities, LNT emphasizes the idea that humans are visiting nature and not nature themselves. This separation is a root cause of so many of the environmental issues of today (as well as health issues, community failures, birth traumas etc). We see ourselves as outside of nature and therefore we can chose to care for it or not. But the truth is we are an interconnected part of nature and we need to live in communion with it.<br>.<br>So what do we talk about instead?<br>.<br>Respect: we talk about the world through the lens of animism and respect the myriad of other consciousnesses that are present. We talk to plants (and always ask permission before picking anything). We give offerings and say thank you to the lands and landscapes we move through. We respect animals by giving them space and honoring their experiences.<br>.<br>Reciprocity: what we get from the land plants or animals deserves care in return. This might mean stewarding a specific piece of land or offering water to a desert plant that we found a lizard living beneath or paying more for local produce.<br>.<br>Interconnection: we point out the ways all the beings of a land exist together. We donâ€™t pick early spring wildflowers because they are an important food source for early pollinators. We pick up our garbage because itâ€™s dangerous for wild animals to get used to eating human food.&nbsp;<br>.<br>Humans exist with nature: We pee outside because water is should cycle back to the earth. We are willing to walk off trail because most landscapes can handle a few small foot steps. We move with care and respect but not with fear that we are ruining something. The earth is meant to hold us. We are of her. &nbsp;<br>.<br>I do understand that human beings have negatively impacted the earth through their actions. I believe the healing the earth needs will not come from humans trying to â€œsaveâ€ it, but instead, from humans who love and respect it as their home, their sister, their mother, and their love.<br>#ecofriendly #savetheplanet #leavenotrace #ecofamily #motherearth #slowlife #naturelover

puntuaciÃ³ mÃ©s alta que la resta (link de l'article al final de l'enllaÃ§)<br>https://www.mountainwilderness.org/2022/01/30/the-olympic-games-and-sustainability/<br><br>Posted @withregram â€¢ @mountain_wilderness_intl The next Winter Olympics are just around the corner, and as usual we question the alleged sustainability of such mega sporting events, but this time we do so on the basis of scientific data.<br><br>Researchers at the University of Lausanne, Switzerland, recently reviewed the social, environmental and economic sustainability of 16 editions of the Summer and Winter Olympic Games.<br><br>The study concludes that the rhetoric of sustainability does not match actual sustainability outcomes and sustainability in the Olympics is clearly declining over time as Salt Lake City (2002) and Albertville (1992) scored higher than all the rest, whereas the Winter Olympics in Sochi in 2014 and the Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro in 2016 had the lowest sustainability scores.<br><br>How will Beijing 2022 and Milano-Cortina 2026 score?<br><br>Link in bio<br><br>MÃ¼ller, M., Wolfe, S.D., Gaffney, C.&nbsp;et al.&nbsp;An evaluation of the sustainability of the Olympic Games.&nbsp;Nat Sustain&nbsp;4,&nbsp;340â€“348 (2021).<br><br>#olympics #olympicgames #sustainability #mountains #climatecrisis #environment #mountainwilderness #IOC #artificialsnow #donoharm #leavenotrace #outdoors #sports #mountainlovers #nature #mountainsmatter #SDGs

Today we're exploring the Saguaro Wilderness in <br>southern ArizonağŸŒµ ğŸŒ. The U.S. Congress designated the Saguaro Wilderness in 1976 and it now has a total of 70,905 acres. The entirety of this wilderness is managed by the National Park Service and is bordered by the Rincon Mountain Wilderness to the east.<br>.<br>Saguaro Wilderness preserves thousands of acres of saguaro cactiğŸŒµ . Sprouting in the shade of other desert plants, the saguaro cactus grows only a few inches in its first five years of life and a few feet in its first 30 years. At age 75 the cactus stands 15 to 20 feet tall and begins developing its first branches as it absorbs water through an extensive root system. A mature cactus can live up to 170 years, often measuring in at over 30 feet tall, weighing 6 to 10 tons, and holding one ton of water. The saguaro is truly the king of the Sonoran Desert.<br>.<br>Nearly 80% of Saguaro National Park has been designated Wilderness. Divided into two units by Tucson, the western Tucson Mountain Unit is relatively flat and the eastern Rincon Mountain Unit rises steeply in places from 2,800 feet to 8,666 feet on Mica Mountain â›°. Saguaro's Wilderness trail system contains approximately 127 miles of maintained trails ğŸ¥¾ , but overnight camping is limited to six sites in the Rincon Mountains.<br>.<br>If you'd like to explore and give back to this particular Wilderness, check out the link in our bio for our 2022 Rincon Creek Trail, Saguaro National Park project. <br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#wildernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #saguarowilderness #designatedwilderness #wilderness #buffelgrass #invasiveplants #stewardship #conservation #nationalparkservice #nationalpark #findyourpark #saguaronationalpark #saguaro #saguaronationalparkwest #saguaronationalparkeast #saveoursaguaros #savethesaguaro #sonorandesert #optoutside #publicland #publiclands #leavenotrace #photography #camping #backpacking #colorpalette #colors #colorwheel

Post_ID: 2764959668844186088	|Post_Code: CZfHCtfvUno	|Owner_ID: 40034464	|Likes: 142	|Time_Stamp: 1643828899	|Tags: ['#santaluciafir', '#abiesbracteata', '#keepitwild', '#ourwild', '#recreateresponsibly', '#leavenotrace']	|Caption: Itâ€™s heartwarming to hear from many people that care about the status of the Santa Lucia Firs on Cone Peak after the Dolan Fire. Fortunately the fire burned at mostly lower intensity through the groves. There were some losses in higher intensity strips which remind us that while the firs are excellently adapted to grow in rocky, fire-resistant places, the trees themselves are not fire resistant if flames find a way to reach them. Overall, the outcome was favorable for the Cone Peak groves, especially considering what could have happened, but the Santa Lucia Fir faces challenges including warming temperatures, drought, and more severe fires entering their fire resistant habitats. As the rarest fir in North America (and possibly the world) these inspiring, gorgeous trees merit protection, preservation and restoration where possible. #santaluciafir #abiesbracteata #keepitwild #ourwild #recreateresponsibly #leavenotrace

It Is something I think about every single time I post a photo - to tag or not to tag? <br><br>While I definitely don't have the answers, I do know a few things. <br><br>âœ¨ Some of the worst offenders of LNT I have met have been people who grew up outdoors. Disrespectful people will be disrespectful. <br><br>âœ¨ Not geotagging is exclusionary. While some people will have access to friends, family, or acquaintances who can help them find good places to recreate, lots of people do not have that circle built up. Just because some people have friends in the know does not mean they deserve the spaces any more than others.<br><br>âœ¨ Crowded spots suck. It takes a ton of the magic away from the outdoors. BUT, to think that I have any more right to that space than anyone else is downright wrong. <br><br>âœ¨ Ultimately, I have a lot to learn about being a good steward to the land. It is a privilege that I have the ability to visit, and I would argue that it's the case for *almost* everyone else out there as well. It is important to be introspective about yourself if you're going to point fingers at others. <br><br>âœ¨ Geotagging can lead people to places they have no business being, from a safety perspective. Either because they don't know or have the correct equipment for the trip, or don't have the experience. This is the main reason I don't geotag some places. <br><br>Like I said, I definitely don't have the answers. Climbing on wet rock - which can be dry to the touch - means taking the risk of breaking a hold and altering a route. Modern cairns are often erected to mark trails as landmarks, or to provide guidance on difficult routes.<br><br>â—ï¸Before youâ€™re tempted to join in, please consider the followingâ—ï¸<br><br>ğŸ§­ An abundance of personal rock piles can cause confusion for hikers looking for navigational aids. It can be easy to mistake these for legitimate cairns, and could result in people getting lost!<br>ğŸ¦‹ Many animals and insects use rocks to live, breed, or for safety; moving even one rock has potential consequences and could have a knock on effect on the entire ecosystem!<br>ğŸŒ¿ Making your own rock piles conflicts with the Leave No Trace principles: a set of ethics that advocate for conservation of outdoor spaces, and leaving the landscape untouched.<br><br>If you come across stacked rocks on your next hikes, itâ€™s best to leave them alone. Post_ID: 2764361169245060306	|Post_Code: CZc-9ZTvDzS	|Owner_ID: 17365821	|Likes: 450	|Time_Stamp: 1643757552	|Tags: ['#rockart', '#petroglyphs', '#indigenous', '#nativeamerican', '#archaeology', '#anthropology', '#respectandprotect', '#leavenotrace', '#navajo', '#dinetah', '#NewMexicoTrue', '#nmoutside', '#nmnomad', '#instagramersnm', '#TravelNM', '#beautiful', '#nmco', '#nmoutdoors', '#onlyinnewmexico', '#newmexicomagazine', '#modernoutdoors', '#natgeoyourshot', '#natgeotravelpic', '#Yourshotphotographer', '#OurPlanetDaily', '#lonelyplanet', '#mylpguide', '#usinterior', '#bealpha', '#divine']	|Caption: WC Petroglyphs 3, NM. This panel is a good example of older and newer glyphs being easy to differentiate. You can easily see the rectilinear glyphs and the small row of figures are lighter than most of the surrounding glyphs, making them younger in age. The exposed rock hasnâ€™t had as much time to develop a new patina (also called desert varnish) as compared to the glyphs that have darkened. The general rule is as they get older, they get closer to matching the color of the rock surface they were pecked into. From what Iâ€™ve seen with most sandstone petroglyphs, the oldest rock art is (usually) the same color as the surface itâ€™s been pecked into. There ARE exceptions to this, especially with stone that hasnâ€™t developed a patina on its surface. How about those flute players in Slides 2 & 3?!<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #navajo #dinetah #NewMexicoTrue #nmoutside #nmnomad #instagramersnm #TravelNM #beautiful_newmexico #nmco #nmoutdoors #onlyinnewmexico #newmexicomagazine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

Post_ID: 2763697361312230608	|Post_Code: CZaoBt_syzQ	|Owner_ID: 11148300825	|Likes: 41	|Time_Stamp: 1643678420	|Tags: ['#mountainmonday']	|Caption: Agiocochook, "Home of the Great Spirit" or "Mother Goddess of the Storm". Either translation is much cooler than the current name ğŸ˜ Happy #mountainmonday<br><br>"Mount Washington is the largest mountain in New Hampshire and falls in the northern third of the Appalachian mountain range in a section called 'the Presidential Range.' The first European ascent of the mountain was performed in June of 1642 by Darby Field accompanied by two Native American guides. It is said that Field wanted to prove to the local Abenaki Chief Passaconaway that he was not subject to the same rules as the Indigenous peoples, who did not climb the summit of the mountain believed to be the realm of divine powers. By climbing the mountain Field dismissed these Indigenous beliefs and assisted the colonistsâ€™ northern expansion." - the Indigenous NH Collaborative collective, https://indigenousnh.com/2018/12/06/the-wobanadenok/<br><br>Taken in January of 2022.

We're under one month away from our 2022 Buenos Aires National Wildlife Refuge project in southern Arizona. We have three spots open for this long-standing project with the Friends of Buenos Aires NWR and we'd love it if you joined us!<br>.<br>We will spend the week working together to remove old interior barbed-wire fences leftover from ranching days. The fence removal is part of an ongoing 15-year project by the Refuge to remove interior fences; only ~18 miles of the fence remains down from over 150 miles of fence that originally existed.<br>.<br>Our volunteer crew will machine or hand roll fences, pull fence posts, and carry them to an ATV to be transported out to trucks for later recycling. Our volunteer group will also modify some boundary fences into wildlife-friendly fences if bordering ranchers will agree.<br>.<br>If you're interested in joining this project, visit the link in bio!<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#wildernessvolunteers #givingsomethingback #wv2022buenosairesnationalwildliferefuge #fenceremoval #wildlifefriendlyfence #wildlife #wildlifemigration #invasives #stewardship #conservation #nationalwildliferefuge #wildliferefuge #buenosairesnationalwildliferefuge #friendsofbuenosairesnationalwildliferefuge #friendsofbanwr #buenosairesnwr #theoutpost #browncanyon #baboquivarimountains #baboquivari #tucson #volunteer #serviceproject #recreateresponsibly #optoutside #publicland #publiclands #leavenotrace #volunteer #hardwork

Post_ID: 2763496421851529987	|Post_Code: CZZ6VqihgMD	|Owner_ID: 2011066695	|Likes: 720	|Time_Stamp: 1643654466	|Tags: ['#LeaveNoTrace', '#Littering', '#RecreateResponsibly', '#FindYourPark', '#EncuentraTuParque']	|Caption: At Pinnacles, we often share the importance of Leaving No Trace and remembering to pack out any waste that you pack in during your visit to the park!<br><br>Most visitors are aware that leaving plastics or other inorganic materials on trail sides is harmful to the environment, but we often encounter discarded items that are thought of as 'biodegradable' strewn in the park, like orange peels or sunflower seed shells.<br><br>While this organic trash will decompose faster than plastic, it still poses a threat to our ecosystems, and creates a nuisance for fellow visitors.<br><br>Leaving food scraps along trails / park infrastructure can attract wildlife to areas of elevated human activity, increasing visitor-wildlife conflicts and habituating our wildlife to human contact.<br><br>As @leavenotraceorg explains, "One apple core will not completely disrupt the local ecosystem, but cumulatively, we know that feeding wildlife damages their health, alters their natural behaviors and exposes them to predators and other dangers."<br><br>When littering of food items occurs along road sides, wildlife feeding on the scraps can be hit by cars, or cause vehicles to swerve.<br><br>Help conserve our park's wildlife and improve the experience of your fellow visitors by always packing out any trash that you pack in, and ensuring that we all Leave No Trace when recreating in Pinnacles!<br><br>#LeaveNoTrace #Littering #RecreateResponsibly #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque <br><br>[Image Description: Fragments of orange peels lie on the ground along the Blue Oak Trail in Pinnacles National Park.]<br><br>Photo: NPS / Reuven Bank

One of my main tools for finding archaeological sites is Google Maps satellite view. I scan the landscape for any shapes that look man-made, primarily looking for hard angles and perfect circles. This spot was found using this method, and I made it out here and climbed up this extremely steep butte to get to the site. Once on top, I found the main structure I had spotted on Google Maps, made of stacked rocks with no mortar. I also found some lesser remnants of structures along the edges of the butte top, which was roughly 500â€™ x 200â€™. I doubt anyone lived up here, and it looked like there may have been some burials judging by the few stone mounds I found topped with flat rocks. One even had a very faint inscription where I could just make out the words â€œI love youâ€. I decided not to take photos of that, and I left immediately after finding the possible graves. I think all of this is from the 18th-19th century, possibly even more modern. This butte may have been used for ceremonial purposes for generations, hence the older structure and the newer graves. Though this was on â€œpublic landâ€, this is the DinÃ©tah, the Navajo homeland, and I understand that this ground is sacred. I walk these lands with reverence. Post_ID: 2762691029955822043	|Post_Code: CZXDNq4rMHb	|Owner_ID: 5934261206	|Likes: 124	|Time_Stamp: 1643558456	|Tags: ['#RecreateResponsibly', '#moab', '#utah', '#leavenotrace', '#beutahful', '#getoutdoors', '#utahisrad', '#recreateresponsibly', '#hiking', '#utahgram', '#utahrocks', '#nature', '#explore', '#outdoor', '#photooftheday', '#landscape', '#petroglyph']	|Caption: There are so many cool areas around Moab and southeastern Utah. Many of these areas contain petroglyphs and pictographs.<br><br>When posting these types of pictures, we feel it is very important to talk about the importance of being respectful and how to #RecreateResponsibly around these sites. <br><br>The art is extremely fragile. If damaged, the site can never be repaired to its original condition.<br><br>While visiting these sites...<br>- Don't touch the rock art or the rock itself! Our skin oils may cause damage.<br>- Don't camp or build fires within 1/4 mile of a rock art site<br>- Don't attempt to remove graffiti, chalking, or anything else from the rock art<br><br>There are many other ways to recreate responsibly around these sites. Also, remember that many people today still consider these sites sacred. Take the utmost caution to limit your impact on the landscape surrounding these areas. The skies still look gray, so we don't bother waiting for our tents to dry before packing up. We plan on going to Pinedale, which requires hiking ten miles off trail to get to a campground to then hitch. Because of that, the path isn't on Guthook. We hike down the pass from our campsite and make it to the turn off. It starts to rain, and Bison and Nude Beach get ahead of me, so I don't have them to double check with we're on the right path. Luckily, there happens to be a lot of day hikers out so whenever I pass a group ask if I'm heading the right way. It's almost miserable hiking in the rain and not being entirely sure I'm on the right path, but I've got Cat Stevens playing in my headphones and as the youth say, "It's a vibe." I catch up to Bison and Nude Beach, and we run into Happy, Ontario, and Goddess. They found a shortcut, so we follow them. We encounter a train of llama-packers? We make it to the trailhead, and it takes us a while to get a hitch. A man and his son offer to take us as long as we're okay with stopping at some of the scenic spots along the way. We're not flush with choices, so we take them up on it and enjoy the overlooks! Once in town we immediately head into the Chinese restaurant and see El Dorado, 13, and Melon. We binge on Chinese food, go to the local park, dry everything out, look for spot to stealth camp (Just Sky July still in effect) and see a moose in the park we're hoping to sleep in (yay!). A thru-hikers enthusiast talks to us and buys us some beer! Once everything is dry we go and eat ice cream outside the grocery store. Nude Beach goes to the Jackalope Motel to sleep, Bison and I go to the park. Bison sets up his tarp for a quick tear down in the morning, and we attempt to get a good night's sleep.<br><br>#newmexico #colorado #wyoming #idaho #montana #embracethebrutality #thetrek #hikingaddict #gooutside #staywild #hikertrash #continentaldividetrail #cdt2021 #mexicotocanada #backpacking #thruhike  #optoutside #camping #longdistancehiking #outdoors #choosemountains #LNT #leavenotrace #camp #summercamp #funnestknowntime

It is also one of Colorado's infamous 14ers, standing proudly at 14,115ft.  Located just a few minutes from Colorado Springs, this is one of the most easily accessible mountains in Colorado!  You can make your way to the summit via car, foot, bicycle, or the cog railway.<br>â €<br>â°Park Hours:<br>9:00am-5:00pm (Oct 1-Thurs before Memorial Day)<br>7:30am-8:00pm (Fri before Memorial Day to Labor Day)<br>7:30am-7:00pm (Tues after Labor Day to Sept 30)<br>â €<br>ğŸ’² Entrance Fees:<br>Adults (16 and Over) - $15 per person (May-Nov) / $10 (Dec-Apr)<br>Children (6 to 15) - $5 per person<br>Carload Discount Rate (Up to 5 passengers) - $50 (May-Nov) / $35 (Dec-Apr)<br>â €<br>âœ”ï¸ While the entire road is paved and well maintained, there are over 150 switchbacks and quite a bit a traffic.  This is also one of the most popular cycling paths in CO, so be aware of your surroundings!  Plan for at least an hour to get from the entrance to the summit (and that is without making any stops).<br>â €<br>â—ï¸ When making your descent avoid overheating your breaks by downshifting to the lowest possible gear! Post_ID: 2761984405763884517	|Post_Code: CZUii70uYXl	|Owner_ID: 49483834901	|Likes: 19	|Time_Stamp: 1643474220	|Tags: ['#hiking', '#naturewalk', '#novicehiker', '#sedona', '#sedonaarizona', '#chickenpoint', '#explorearizona', '#leavenotrace', '#respectnature', '#trails', '#naturegram', '#midwestblogger', '#sdblogger', '#getoutside']	|Caption: Tips for novice hikers ğŸ¥¾â›°ï¸<br><br>Now when I say novice hiker, I'm talking to my fellow Midwesterners who refer to the slightly hilly nature walk along the river of your local state park as a "hike."<br><br>It's all good. I'm right there with you! ğŸ˜… They're all "hikes" to me too! But it is important to note that when you're traveling to more mountainous regions, the preparations you take for your hikes will look a little different.<br><br>So let's take a look at a few things to remember:<br><br>ğŸ¥¾ Dress appropriately. Sturdy, snug fitting shoes. Breathable, moisture wicking clothing. And layers. Be prepared for temperature changes and your body's eventual heat up by dressing in layers!<br><br>ğŸ¥¾ Plan ahead. Check the weather. Review a map of your trail beforehand. And if possible, download the map to your phone.<br><br>ğŸ¥¾ Bring a backpack. On your nature walk through the Palisades, this may not be necessary. I mean, you can see the car from the middle of the trail! But when traveling longer distances over unfamiliar terrain, you're going to want a backpack of essentials.<br><br>ğŸ¥¾ What essentials go in the backpack? A large bottle of water, snacks, and navigation equipment - map and compass, are a must. You may also want to consider the following: first aid kit, sunscreen, fire starter, blanket, flashlight, and power bank for portable charging.<br><br>ğŸ¥¾ Finally, whether you're planning to enjoy the perfect summit beer, sit down for a picnic, or snarf down an energy bar, always, always remember to leave no trace! All trash and materials not from the area should be packed up and brought back with you for proper disposal. It's our responsibility to be good stewards of the earth and leave the land as we found it!<br><br>Happy hiking ğŸ˜Š<br><br>*Photos from Chicken Point, Sedona, AZ<br><br>#hiking #naturewalk #novicehiker #sedona #sedonaarizona #chickenpoint #explorearizona #leavenotrace #respectnature #trails #naturegram #midwestblogger #sdblogger #getoutside

Like how to improve various processes and make it more efficient and profitable and most importantly, more safe where applicable. Post_ID: 2761936197121436018	|Post_Code: CZUXlaBt2ly	|Owner_ID: 2228174887	|Likes: 399	|Time_Stamp: 1643468518	|Tags: ['#SustainableSaturday', '#visitusaparks', '#thisismyroute']	|Caption: Happy #SustainableSaturday! â <br>â <br>This week we are bringing you some hiking etiquette tips! ğŸ¥¾ğŸ¥¾ğŸ¥¾â <br>â <br>1. Travel on durable surfaces (stay on-trail): Concentrating travel on trails reduces the likelihood that multiple routes will develop and scar the landscape. It is better to have one well-designed route than many poorly chosen paths. Lots of paths can lead to erosion, which can damage slopes and make it hard for vegetation to live there. ğŸŒ¾ğŸŒ¿ğŸŒ±â <br>â <br>2. If you must go off-trail (this is usually only necessary in the backcountry), search for the most durable surfaces to walk on, so you leave less of an impact. Rocks, gravel snow and ice are the most durable to travel on (though beware in desert environments of cryptobiotic soil - this is created by living organisms such as algae, cyanobacteria, and fungi and takes hundreds of years to grow!). ğŸ¤¯â <br>â <br>Traveling with respect through our beautiful wild spaces will help preserve and protect them for future generations. ğŸŒ ğŸŒ ğŸŒâ <br>â <br>.â <br>.â <br>ğŸ“Western Mono/Monache, Numu (Northern Paiute) and Eastern Mono/Monache landâ <br> ğŸ“·: @chrisslagle_ #visitusaparks #thisismyroute

Have I mentioned how Iâ€™m a sucker for horse imagery? All of these are obviously historic, and they could have been made by a number of people- local indigenous, Mormon emigrants, ranchers, etc. Theyâ€™re definitely old based on the patina returning to the exposed rock, and therefore they have historical relevance. Knowing who passed this way 100 or 200 years ago is much more interesting and informative in the sense you have to consider what life was like back then. They were moving livestock, mining, hunting, homesteading. There was almost always a purpose for someone to be out here, and it usually had something to do with surviving in this landscape. And they loved their horses, so much so that this guy made a portrait with him & his horse. Slide 2 is very lovingly drawn and quite anatomically accurate, though I think that truncated body is hilarious. Slide 3 is the most stylized of the bunch, and I love that the mane is depicted. I might have to start an Instagram just for horse petroglyphs.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br><br>#rockart #petroglyphs #indigenous #nativeamerican #archaeology #anthropology #respectandprotect #leavenotrace #Utahspots #utahunique #youtah #utahisrad #Utahgram #visitutah #werutah #wowutah #naturalutah #utahillustrated #horse #equine #modernoutdoors #natgeoyourshot&nbsp; #natgeotravelpic #Yourshotphotographer #OurPlanetDaily #lonelyplanet #mylpguide #usinterior #bealpha #divine_deserts @sonyalpha

For the most accurate weather forecast for your trip, navigate to Plan Your Visit from our home page, and click on Weather. This will take you to the National Weather Service forecast, which gives you the exact weather in the center of the park. <br><br>As Shawna explains, "other weather apps will show the weather in neighboring towns, which is usually 10-15F off. This makes a huge difference in the summer when it is 105F instead of 90F, or when it is 30F in the campground on a brisk winterâ€™s night instead of a humid 45F."<br><br>Shawna recommends these additional website tips to help visitors plan their trip to Pinnacles:<br><br>â—‰ From the Plan Your Visit tab, you can select Things to Do. From here, visit the Hiking Trails tab to read detailed descriptions of the trails. <br><br>â—‰ From the Maps page in the navigation bar, you can view the park map and familiarize yourself with the trails and roadways prior to arrival. If you look closely at the map, you will notice little gray triangles at trail intersections. These triangles are areas on the trails where there will be signs indicating the trail names and distances. The numbers between these map markers indicate the mileage. <br><br>â—‰ Finally, click on the Alerts in Effect at the top of our page. Post_ID: 2761295964541885589	|Post_Code: CZSGAy-PRyV	|Owner_ID: 3544188636	|Likes: 154	|Time_Stamp: 1643392151	|Tags: ['#California', '#abandonedcalifornia', '#urbex', '#urbandecay', '#abandoned', '#forgotten', '#waterpark', '#desert', '#desertvibes', '#stories', '#vandalism', '#thisiswhywecanthavenicethings', '#leavenotrace', '#livetoexplore', '#wanderlust', '#urbanart', '#urbanphotography', '#abandonedplaces', '#abandoned', '#abandoned']	|Caption: In the 1950s local businessman Bob Byers began planning a lake for use by his extended family, which he named after his wife, Dolores. The lake was fed by underground springs that were, in turn, fed by the Mojave Aquifer. In 1962 a campground adjacent to the lake opened and travelers on highway 15 began to use the campground. Over the next 25 years, rides and attractions were added and Lake Dolores evolved into a waterpark dubbed "The Fun Spot in the Desert." After a downturn in popularity, the park closed in the late 1980s.<br>-<br>In 1990 Byers sold the park and the new owners recreated the park with a 50s theme, called Rock-a-Hoola waterpark which opened on July 4, 1998. The park quickly amassed $3 million dollars in debt and added a $4.4 MM dollar judgment to an employee who was paralyzed. The owners filed bankruptcy in 2000, and the park was eventually returned to Dolores Byers, whose husband had passed. Dolores sold the park in 2001 and died a month later.<br>-<br>After a 400,000 renovation the park reopened in May 2002 as Discovery Waterpark, but was only opened intermittently and closed for good in the summer of 2004. Many installations were sold off in 2009, including the slides, which became Colossal Canyon and Zero-60 Raceway at Cultus Lake Waterpark in B.C. Trespassers on the property stole metal and wires from the buildings, smashing sinks, toilets, and anything breakable, tagging over the 2013 artwork, and eventually setting the park on fire, burning many buildings to the ground in 2018.<br>-<br>In early 2020, a private investor bought the property and obtained conditional use permits to begin construction, but COVID hit. The park had been slated to reopen in 2023, but it appears plans are just delayed.<br>-<br>-<br>-<br>-<br>#California #abandonedcalifornia #urbex #urbandecay #abandoned #forgotten #waterpark #desert #desertvibes #stories #vandalism #thisiswhywecanthavenicethings #leavenotrace #livetoexplore #wanderlust #urbanart #urbanphotography #abandonedplaces #abandoned_junkies #abandoned_addiction

We collect them back for commercial composting.<br><br>It was a big decision for us when we started Eat Me Greens. In the end, we decided against recyclables , which would have been much cheaper for us. But often, public recycling ends up being shipped overseas under contract where it is often not handled correctly.<br><br>It seemed ludicrous that we would argue for low food miles but then have massive "waste miles" and even then for it all to be dumped in landfills anyway.<br><br>Whilst PLA will break down eventually in a landfill, it takes a long time. In an incinerator, they create less toxic residue than plastics. Compostables therefore, were the best option we could choose.<br><br>Commercial composting uses enzymes and correct pressure and temperature to make sure nothing is left for future generations to deal with.<br><br>We can't do it without you! Post_ID: 2761248968170617229	|Post_Code: CZR7U6MOTmN	|Owner_ID: 35929030334	|Likes: 511	|Time_Stamp: 1643386549	|Tags: ['#leavenotrace', '#exploretheoutdoors', '#getoutside', '#exploremore', '#happypeoplehike', '#hikemoreworryless', '#sheexplores', '#hikingadventures', '#hikinggirl', '#adventureanywhere', '#womenwhohike', '#visitcolorado', '#optoutside']	|Caption: Happy Friday! <br><br>While hiking is now my favorite activity, I really only got serious about it a couple years ago. So today I want to share one of the most important things I think you should know about getting started hiking: the 7 principles of @leavenotraceorg!<br><br>The basics of leaving no trace as self explanatory - leave no evidence that you were there! But there are actually 7 principles provided by the Leave No Trace Center for Outdoor Ethics. <br><br>Leave what you find: This includes not taking rocks with you, not digging trenches for tents, not leaving anything behind and not damaging any live trees or plants (like by carving on a tree).<br><br>Plan ahead and prepare: Planning ahead will ensure your own safety and help you have a better time. Ways to plan ahead include checking the weather, understanding the terrain youâ€™re visiting and having necessary items such as a map.<br><br>Dispose of waste properly: This not only includes trash, but human waste. Make sure you know ahead of time if waste should be packed out or it is allowed to be buried (this depends on the terrain). If you dig a hole, make sure it is out of the way of others and far from water sources. <br><br>Travel on durable surfaces: This means stay on the trail. Donâ€™t take shortcuts as if it can damage fragile vegetation. <br><br>Minimize campfire impacts: Before building a fire, make sure you know the current fire danger in the area. It is always better to use fire rings that already exist when possible. <br><br>Respect wildlife: Never feed, bother or get too close to wildlife. Getting too close is not only dangerous to the animal but also to yourself. <br><br>Be considerate to others: Be considerate by not playing music on loud speakers, giving uphill hikers the right of way and keeping your pet in control if you bring one! <br><br>Save this post as a reminder!<br><br>How do you protect the landscape and minimize your impact when exploring the outdoors?<br><br>#leavenotrace #exploretheoutdoors #getoutside #exploremore #happypeoplehike #hikemoreworryless #sheexplores #hikingadventures #hikinggirl #adventureanywhere #womenwhohike #visitcolorado #optoutside

Post_ID: 2761202702763851797	|Post_Code: CZRwzqLFoAV	|Owner_ID: 41348624723	|Likes: 274	|Time_Stamp: 1643381034	|Tags: []	|Caption: Leave No Trace Principle 2: Travel and Camp on Durable Surfaces â¬‡ï¸<br><br>Continuing with our LNT series, letâ€™s talk about principle 2!<br><br>Choosing durable surfaces to travel and camp on greatly impacts the degradation of the environment. <br><br>ğŸ¥¾RULE OF THUMB: stay on the provided trails. Trails are built to be able to limit the destruction of the nearby areas, to keep the traffic in a designated area. So, whenever possible, stay on the trail.<br><br>ğŸ¥¾BUT, LETâ€™S BE REAL, there are times we have all gone off the trail! Whether youâ€™re searching for a private â€œbathroomâ€ area, taking a lunch break,  finding a campsite, or scrambling up some rock to get to a vista, itâ€™s just part of hiking! <br><br>ğŸª¨ Because of this, itâ€™s important to BE CONSCIOUS of where you travel off trail. Rocky areas are often able to withstand a lot more travel than vegetation and living soil. <br><br>ğŸ‘£ If you must travel through these areas, be conscious of your impact. (Sometimes this means spreading out from your group (vegetation), sometimes it means following exact footprints (soil))<br><br>ğŸ•CAMPING on durable surfaces:<br>Choose a campsite that either already has very high traffic (no vegetation left) or, in less trafficked areas, find locations you can have the least impact on. Generally, rock and sand are great areas to set up camp, as they will be able to withstand campers. <br><br>â›ºï¸ğŸ¥˜CAMP COOKING: Set up camp kitchens on Rocky areas to avoid constant trampling on vegetation and soil. <br><br>This principle is EXTENSIVE and every situation differs. Your situation changes in different locations, the type of trip, and the local environment. We highly recommend you go check out lnt.org for more information on how to implement this principle, but we hope this gave you a good idea of the general guidelines!<br><br>Overall, it is our jobs to take into consideration the environment around us to decide how we can best limit our impact on each trip.<br><br>We also feel itâ€™s important to recognize that while â€œstay on the trailâ€ is a good rule of thumb, there are circumstances when you just CANâ€™T. Being able to know how to handle those moments and travel off trail responsibly is super important and can help us all to take better care of these lands!

Good times. I think I broke the people I was doing the pennine way with though. Next day we did 25 miles just so we could use a campsite with a toilet and a pub. Day after that I left the poor buggers behind and speed marched 38 miles across some of the highest points in Yorkshire to try n make up time. Post_ID: 2760161525668706104	|Post_Code: CZOEEicLvc4	|Owner_ID: 2024810350	|Likes: 72	|Time_Stamp: 1643256916	|Tags: ['#oceanfriendlybusiness', '#oceanfriendly', '#takebackthetap', '#cutthecutlery', '#leavenotrace', '#livelikealocal', '#refill', '#circular', '#circulareconomy', '#surfrider', '#uclueletcampground', '#pacificrim', '#ucluelet', '#myucluelet', '#bethechange']	|Caption: Tucked away, off to the side of the heart of Ucluelet, is @uclueletcampground <br><br>Surfrider would like to recognize the exceptional efforts this local business has put into become an Ocean Friendly Business! <br><br>Founded in 1982, this campground, composed of 125 unique and forested sites sits along the waters edge.<br><br>The love of the ocean is clear and many steps have been taken to ensure waste reduction on site. <br><br>The transformed an old shed into their new recycling centre for guests accepting a range of items from cigarette butts to propane tanks. <br><br>They use icons and pictures, and have accessible stations as well to increase equity and inclusion of all guests, so that language and mobility are not hindering factors to waste diversion. <br><br>The Recycling centre is also home to a sharing library, where guests can leave unwanted supplies, such as tents, tarps, and other camping supplies for future guests. This sharing culture is part of a larger movement towards a circular economy, and moves away from the linear take-make-waste economy. <br><br>Since they created the recycling centre, they have reduced their waste by roughly 50%!! <br><br>The @uclueletcampground asks guests to follow a code of conduct, pledging to Take Back the Tap and refill reusable water bottles, leave no trace, and Cut the Cutlery, avoiding single-use cutlery and plates. <br><br>Beyond looking after the ocean, they donate all refundables, collected at the recycling centre, to feed the local community ğŸ’š<br><br>Thanks for being AWESOME Ucluelet Campground!! <br><br>ğŸ“¸ by @uclueletcampground <br><br>#oceanfriendlybusiness #oceanfriendly #takebackthetap #cutthecutlery #leavenotrace #livelikealocal #refill #circular #circulareconomy #surfrider #uclueletcampground #pacificrim #ucluelet #myucluelet #bethechange

Post_ID: 2760078930242506807	|Post_Code: CZNxSndJRA3	|Owner_ID: 7937511140	|Likes: 111	|Time_Stamp: 1643247070	|Tags: ['#restoration', '#rangers', '#jmt', '#johnmuirtrail', '#wildernessrestoration', '#sustainable', '#camping', '#natural', '#naturalization', '#leavenotrace', '#lnt']	|Caption: Before and after - this is what campsite restoration looks like! <br><br>Picture 1 shows an illegal campsite that had been heavily used, leaving the area without vegetation or healthy soil. Picture 2 shows the area after the soil has been decompacted to allow for aeration, moisture retention, and root growth. It was then covered in a layer of topsoil and dead vegetation. If left alone, this vegetation will start to decompose, adding necessary nutrients back into the soil and returning this patch to a healthy state. <br><br>Rangers and restoration crews work hard to return these areas to their natural state. If you see something that looks like picture 2, please leave it as is and find a more sustainable spot to stop!<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>.<br>#restoration #rangers #jmt #johnmuirtrail #wildernessrestoration #sustainable #camping #natural #naturalization #leavenotrace #lnt

Post_ID: 2760036551086853266	|Post_Code: CZNnp6yoEyS	|Owner_ID: 13698144	|Likes: 98	|Time_Stamp: 1643242018	|Tags: ['#rambling', '#environment', '#nature', '#yewtreepilgrimage', '#wildcamping', '#solocamping', '#womenwhohike', '#wildcampinguk', '#getoutside', '#womenwildcamping', '#womenwhocamp', '#getoutdoors', '#woodlands', '#natureconnection', '#leavenotrace', '#hiking', '#exploring', '#msrhubbahubba', '#msrgear', '#barefeet', '#righttoroam', '#trespass', '#landscapeoffreedom']	|Caption: As a relative newcomer to the world of wild camping Iâ€™m still testing out what I need to feel safe. Generally this means finding a place thatâ€™s far enough away from people to not get noticed, but near enough should I need to scream or run for help. If this sounds overly cautious, itâ€™s not. These concerns for women are legitimate and real. <br><br>Back in late October, before going into hibernation mode for winter, I got busted by a local landowner whilst setting up my tent in a corner of a field. It was dusk, my kit was out of the bag and I was caught peg-handed. He asked if I wanted to come in for dinner and my instincts - and rumbly tummy - said yes. He was a very wealthy man, insisting on telling me the price of most of the objects in his home. A tour of the house turned into what felt like an inventory! Clearly baffled at my choice to still sleep out in my tent - his house had many spare rooms and the weather was fierce - he still very kindly brought me a warm cup of tea in the morning to see me on my way. <br><br>That following evening, stretching beyond my comfort zone to camp in more of a remote spot than usual, turned out to be one of the most magical wild camps yet. After many hours walking and scouting, feet sore but spirits high, an ancient apple orchard was found, nestled on the edge of a field of monocrop. An encircling barrier of brambles provided plenty of cover, and snuggling down deep in my sleeping bag I looked up at a sky of a million stars. At some point much later a badger padded past, stopping to sniff the air beneath a moonlit dappled branch. I understood then how this land was theirs. <br>â£. <br>.â£<br>.â£<br>#rambling #environment #nature #yewtreepilgrimage #wildcamping #solocamping #womenwhohike #wildcampinguk #getoutside #womenwildcamping #womenwhocamp #getoutdoors #woodlands #natureconnection #leavenotrace #hiking #exploring â£#msrhubbahubba #msrgear #barefeet #righttoroam #trespass #landscapeoffreedom
